defaulthttp://locality.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/Public-Services-Civil-Society-and-Diseconomies-of-Scale.pdf 
default21default A 2013 VCSE survey by Locality found that 42% of respondents believe contracts have become larger in the last five years and a further 52% expect them to become larger still over the next five years. 80% said this would provide them with less opportunities and a lower range and quality of services in their area. 
default22default A recent NCVO survey found that 23 out of 46 respondents said the scale of contracts has prevented their organisation bidding for work. One respondent noted how a county council have moved to county wide contracts rather than local ones, and that this has opened up the market to national providers to the detriment of local organisations. The full survey results can be provided on request. 
default23default The Federation of Small Businesses points out that the UK has amongst the largest average contract values in the EU. In France and Germany, with larger populations and similar size economies, average contract sizes are significantly smaller 
defaulthttp://www.fsb.org.uk/policy/rpu/scotland/assets/publi_spec_procurabridjuly2012.pdf 
default24default An NCVO report The Work Programme – Perceptions and Experiences of the Voluntary Sector identifies management fees of between 15-20 percent 
defaulthttp://www.ncvo.org.uk/images/documents/practical_support/public_services/SIG%20survey%202012%20report.pdf 
default25 Ibid 
default26default A recent NPC report highlighted a case in Bradford where the City Council had reduced the number of homelessness services providers from 11 to 4, and required providers to demonstrate their financial strength while squeezing pricing. As a result, fewer VCS organisations bid for the contracts. 
defaulthttp://www.thinknpc.org/publications/governance-in-the-new-commissioning-landscape/ 
default27default A recent survey by Compact Voice found that almost 90 percent of voluntary sector respondents believe that public bodies will still focus on lower cost rather than social value when funding 
defaulthttp://www.compactvoice.org.uk/blogs/compact-voice/2013/08/07/local-compact-survey-results-2013-briefing-3-social-value 
default28default From NCVO members in two recent surveys. 
defaultAlso feedback from Compact Voice, the NCVO Public Services Delivery Network and other voluntary sector partners.
default 
default29default One NCVO member reports how four years ago a public health body let a smoking cessation contract where the contract specification was 80 percent quality and 20 percent price. This year the contract was re-let at 60 percent price, 40 percent quality. 
default30default Good practice does exist. For its Café West Tender, York City Council held a number of events where they engaged with potential providers to discuss how social value should be built into the specification of the contact. Items in the specification included employing local people, working with people with disabilities and creating employment pathways. 
